The [Avro 504](/Avro_504) stands as a testament to the sheer, stubborn utility of a simple design. One might even call it… persistent. Introduced in 1913, this multi-role [military aircraft](/Military_aircraft) family, originally conceived by the [Avro aircraft company](/Avro) and later built by a veritable consortium of manufacturers, managed to embed itself in aviation history not through flashy heroics, but through sheer, unglamorous ubiquity. Its production span was almost two decades, a duration that would make most modern designs blush and then spontaneously combust. From 1913 to 1932, over 10,000 units rolled off assembly lines, including those in Japan and the Soviet Union, not to mention a litany of other international producers. This makes it the single most-produced aircraft type to see military service during the entirety of [World War I](/World_War_I) – a rather dubious honour, one might argue, for a machine that largely found its true calling away from the front lines.

## General information

The [Avro 504](/Avro_504) wasn't just an aircraft; it was a phenomenon, a workhorse that stubbornly refused to fade into obscurity. Its versatility was less a testament to groundbreaking engineering and more a reflection of the desperate needs of early military aviation. It served primarily as a [trainer](/Trainer_(aircraft)), molding the raw recruits who would go on to fly more specialized (and perhaps more glamorous) machines. Yet, its early life saw it briefly — and rather awkwardly — pressed into service as a rudimentary [fighter](/Fighter_aircraft) and even a light [bomber](/Bomber).

The sheer scale of its production is frankly exhausting to contemplate. [Avro](/Avro), the original [aerospace manufacturer](/Aerospace_manufacturer), saw its design replicated globally. Its primary users included the burgeoning air arms of the [Royal Flying Corps](/Royal_Flying_Corps) (RFC) and the [Royal Naval Air Service](/Royal_Naval_Air_Service) (RNAS) during the Great War, but its influence stretched far beyond the British Isles. The total count of built aircraft, a staggering 11,303 units, includes all licensed foreign production, from Japanese factories to Soviet workshops, proving that sometimes, the simplest solutions are the most enduring.

### History

*   **Manufactured:** 1913–1932. A run of almost twenty years for a design born in the infancy of flight is less a triumph of foresight and more an indicator of how long it takes for bureaucracy to replace a perfectly adequate, if uninspired, solution.
*   **Introduction date:** 1913. Just in time for the world to descend into chaos, ensuring it had plenty of work.
*   **First flight:** 18 September 1913. A rather unremarkable date for a rather unremarkable, yet utterly vital, aircraft.
*   **Retired:** 1934. It outlived its war, its replacements, and probably a few of its original pilots. A true survivor, or perhaps just too stubborn to quit.

The production figures alone are enough to make one sigh with the weight of history. A total of 8,970 Avro 504s were manufactured during the tumultuous years of [World War I](/World_War_I) itself. This sustained output continued for nearly two decades, finally ceasing in 1932, long after the cannons had fallen silent and the world had moved on to more sophisticated (and equally destructive) aerial platforms. This lengthy production run, culminating in over 10,000 units, solidifies its status as the most-produced aircraft to serve in any military capacity during the First World War, a somewhat ironic legacy for a machine that spent most of its career teaching others to fly.

## Design and development

The [Avro 504](/Avro_504) didn't spring from the ether fully formed and revolutionary. It was, rather predictably, a refinement of existing ideas, specifically a direct evolution of the earlier [Avro 500](/Avro_500). Its initial design brief, which one can only assume was scribbled on a napkin somewhere, aimed for a dual role: both training and private flying. Because, naturally, what every private aviator needed was a robust, easily maintained biplane that could also teach fledgling military pilots the rudiments of flight.

[Fred "Freddie" Raynham](/F._P._Raynham), a name that probably meant something to someone at the time, piloted its inaugural flight from the hallowed (and slightly muddy) grounds of [Brooklands](/Brooklands) on 18 September 1913. Under the hood, or rather, exposed to the elements, was an 80&#160;hp (60&#160;kW) [Gnome Lambda](/Gnome_Lambda) seven-cylinder [rotary engine](/Rotary_engine). These early rotary engines were a marvel of their time, with the entire engine block spinning around a stationary crankshaft, offering smooth power delivery but also a rather prodigious appetite for castor oil, which had the added effect of coating the pilot in a fine, lubricating mist. Delightful.

Structurally, the 504 was a rather conventional, if sturdy, machine for its era. It was a [two-bay](/Interplane_struts) [biplane](/Biplane), meaning its wings were braced by two sets of vertical struts on each side. The entire airframe was crafted primarily from wood, a material choice that speaks volumes about the technology of the day. Its [fuselage](/Fuselage) was of a square-section design, which, while perhaps not the epitome of aerodynamic elegance, certainly contributed to its robust and straightforward construction. The philosophy here was clearly "simple, strong, and easy to build," which, as history would prove, was precisely what was needed.

### Manufacturers

The popularity and sheer demand for the [Avro 504](/Avro_504) during and after [World War I](/World_War_I) meant that [A. V. Roe and Co](/Avro) Ltd. alone couldn't possibly keep up. Consequently, production was licensed to a truly impressive, almost alarming, number of other companies. It was the aviation equivalent of a pop song everyone covered, some with more success than others. The following is a partial list of those who, for better or worse, put their stamp on the ubiquitous 504:

*   **[A. V. Roe and Co](/Avro) Ltd.**, with operations at Park Works in [Newton Heath](/Newton_Heath), Manchester, and later expanding to Hamble Aerodrome near Southampton, Hants. The original purveyors of this enduring design.
*   **[Australian Aircraft and Engineering](/Australian_Aircraft_%26_Engineering)**, based in Sydney, NSW, Australia. Because even down under, they needed trainers.
*   **Bleriot and SPAD Aircraft Works**, located in Addlestone. A rather illustrious name to be associated with such a utilitarian machine.
*   **[The Brush Electrical Engineering Co Ltd](/Brush_Electrical_Machines)**, Loughborough. Evidently, if you could build electrical machinery, you could build airplanes. The interwar industrial pivot was a wild time.
*   **[Canadian Aeroplanes Ltd](/Canadian_Aeroplanes_Ltd)**, operating out of [Toronto, Ontario](/Toronto), Canada. The Canadians, ever practical, took to it with gusto.
*   **[The Eastbourne Aviation Co Ltd](/Eastbourne_Aviation_Company)**, from [Eastbourne](/Eastbourne). Another regional player in the grand scheme of mass production.
*   **Aero Historic**, Parana, Argentina. Even South America recognized a good, basic design when it saw one.
*   **[Fabrica Militar de Aviones](/Fabrica_Militar_de_Aviones)**, situated in [Cordoba, Argentina](/C%C3%B3rdoba,_Argentina). Further south, the Argentinians were clearly committed.
*   **[Frederick Sage and Co Ltd](/Frederick_Sage_and_Co_Ltd)**, with facilities in [Peterborough](/Peterborough) and London. From furniture to fuselages, a common enough transition in early aviation.
*   **[The Grahame-White Aviation Co Ltd](/Grahame-White)**, at Hendon Aerodrome, London. Another prominent early aviation pioneer contributing to the 504's omnipresence.
*   **[Harland and Wolff](/Harland_and_Wolff) Ltd**, Belfast. The shipbuilders, naturally, turned their hand to aircraft when the need arose.
*   **The Henderson Scottish Aviation Factory**, Aberdeen. A nod to regional industrial capacity.
*   **[Hewlett and Blondeau Ltd](/Hewlett_%26_Blondeau)**, from [Luton](/Luton). Even smaller firms joined the production effort.
*   **[Humber Limited](/Humber_Limited)**, Coventry. Famous for cars and bicycles, they, too, diversified.
*   **Morgan and Co**, [Leighton Buzzard](/Leighton_Buzzard). The list continues to grow, illustrating the distributed nature of wartime manufacturing.
*   **[Nakajima Hikoki Seisaku Sho](/Nakajima_Aircraft_Company)**, in [Ohta-Machi](/%C5%8Ctemachi), Tokyo, Japan. The Japanese were early adopters and significant producers, indicating the design's global appeal and utility.
*   **[Parnall & Sons](/Parnall_%26_Sons)**, Bristol. Another British firm contributing to the effort.
*   **Regent Carriage**, Fulham. From carriages to aircraft, another logical (for the time) manufacturing pivot.
*   **S. E. Saunders Ltd**, East Cowes, Isle of Wight. Proving that even island-based companies could get in on the action.
*   **Savages Ltd**, [King's Lynn](/King%27s_Lynn). The sheer number of companies involved is almost comical.
*   **[SABCA](/Societe_Anonyme_Belge_de_Constructions_Aeronautiques)**, Brussels, Belgium. European nations also required robust trainers for their air forces.
*   **[The Sunbeam Motor Car Co Ltd](/Sunbeam_Motor_Car_Company)**, Wolverhampton. Yet another automotive manufacturer lending its production capabilities.
*   **[TNCA](/TNCA)**, located at Balbuena field in Mexico City. The Mexicans, too, found the 504 to be an ideal platform.
*   **[Yokosuka Naval Arsenal](/Yokosuka_Naval_Arsenal)**, Japan. The Imperial Japanese Navy also produced variants for their own training needs.

This extensive list underscores the [Avro 504](/Avro_504)'s role as a foundational aircraft for numerous air forces worldwide, not just a British curiosity. It was, in essence, the "standard issue" basic trainer for an entire generation of pilots across multiple continents.

## Operational history

The [Avro 504](/Avro_504)'s operational life was less about glorious dogfights and more about the quiet, persistent grind of training, punctuated by moments of desperate improvisation.

Early in its career, before the brutal reality of [World War I](/World_War_I) fully set in, a modest number of these aircraft were acquired by the [Royal Flying Corps](/Royal_Flying_Corps) (RFC) and the [Royal Naval Air Service](/Royal_Naval_Air_Service) (RNAS). These pioneers were promptly shipped off to France at the outbreak of hostilities, where they quickly encountered the harsh realities of aerial combat. In a rather unfortunate, yet historically significant, turn of events, one of these early RFC 504s became the very first British aircraft to be shot down by German forces, an inglorious distinction it earned on 22 August 1914. The pilot, [2nd Lt.](/Second_Lieutenant) Vincent Waterfall, and his navigator, [Lt](/Lieutenant) Charles George Gordon Bayly, both from [5 Sqn RFC](/No._5_Squadron_RFC), met their end that day, a stark reminder of the fragile nature of early aviation.

However, the RNAS, with a characteristic flair for the audacious, found a brief, more aggressive use for the 504. Four of these aircraft were cobbled together to form a special flight with the rather ambitious goal of bombing the infamous [Zeppelin](/Zeppelin) works at [Friedrichshafen](/Friedrichshafen) on the shores of [Lake Constance](/Lake_Constance). On 21 November 1914, three of these intrepid machines departed from [Belfort](/Belfort) in north-eastern France, each burdened with four rather paltry 20&#160;lb (9&#160;kg) bombs. While one aircraft was lost to enemy fire, the raid itself was, against all odds, deemed successful. Several direct hits were scored on the airship sheds, and, critically, the hydrogen generating plant was destroyed, a significant blow to German airship operations. This early bombing raid, undertaken by aircraft barely capable of the task, showcases the desperate ingenuity of the nascent air services. It was also the first British aircraft to make a bombing raid over Germany, a feat that would be overshadowed by larger, more dedicated bombers later in the war, but a first nonetheless.

It didn't take long for the 504 to become utterly obsolete as a frontline combat aircraft. Its speed, armament, and general performance simply couldn't keep pace with the rapidly evolving aerial landscape of [World War I](/World_War_I). But, like a seasoned actor who finds their true calling in character roles, the 504 truly came into its own as a [trainer](/Trainer_(aircraft)). Thousands upon thousands of these aircraft were churned out during the war, transforming raw recruits into pilots. The most significant production types were the 504J and the truly mass-produced 504K. The latter was particularly notable for its modified engine bearers, a clever design adaptation that allowed it to accommodate a wide range of engines. This flexibility was crucial in mitigating the chronic engine shortages that plagued wartime production. By the Armistice in 1918, a staggering 8,340 [Avro 504s](/Avro_504) had been produced, a testament to its indispensable role in the training pipeline.

In a curious twist of fate, during the harsh winter of 1917–18, some converted 504Js and 504Ks were pressed back into a combat role. They were used to equip Home Defence squadrons of the RFC, replacing the notoriously underperforming and aging [B.E.2cs](/Royal_Aircraft_Factory_B.E.2), which simply couldn't climb high enough to intercept incoming [Zeppelins](/Zeppelin). These Avros were modified into single-seaters, fitted with a [Lewis gun](/Lewis_gun) mounted above the upper wing on a [Foster mounting](/Foster_mounting) (a rather ingenious, if precarious, mechanism allowing the pilot to reload and clear jams). They were powered by 100&#160;hp (75&#160;kW) Gnome or 110&#160;hp (82&#160;kW) Le Rhône engines, giving them a slight edge in altitude performance over their predecessors. A total of 274 converted [Avro 504Js and Ks](/Avro_504) were distributed among eight home defence squadrons in 1918, with 226 still serving as fighters when the war finally concluded. It's a rather grim joke that a trainer was considered a *better* fighter than a purpose-built design, but that was the reality.

Following the end of the war, the 504's story continued, albeit in a different vein. While it remained the standard [trainer](/Trainer_(aircraft)) for the newly formed [RAF](/RAF), the market was flooded with surplus aircraft. These were snapped up for both civil and military applications. Over 300 504Ks found their way onto the civil register in Britain alone, embarking on second careers. They were used for continued flight training, for the burgeoning industry of pleasure flying, for the rather mundane task of banner towing, and even for the exhilarating (and often dangerous) spectacle of [barnstorming](/Barnstorming) exhibitions. This phenomenon mirrored the post-[World War I](/World_War_I) aviation landscape in North America, where surplus [Curtiss JN-4s](/Curtiss_JN-4) and [Standard J](/Standard_J)-1s were similarly repurposed. These civilian 504s, defying expectations, continued to fly in significant numbers well into the 1930s, refusing to gracefully exit the stage.

Meanwhile, in the newly formed [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union), an embryonic [air service](/Soviet_Air_Forces) emerged from the ashes of the First World War. They, too, found the [Avro 504](/Avro_504) indispensable. They utilized both original British-built examples and their own reverse-engineered copy, affectionately dubbed the U-1 Avrushka ("Little Avro"), for primary training throughout the early 1920s. These Russian variants were typically powered by locally manufactured copies of the [Gnome Monosoupape](/Gnome_Monosoupape) rotary engine. The U-1 Avrushka eventually gave way to its successor, the [Polikarpov Po-2](/Polikarpov_Po-2) (initially known as the U-2), which would go on to become the most produced biplane in *all* of aviation history. The original Avro-derived types, however, remained in Soviet service until the late 1920s, and even longer in other parts of the world.

In a particularly unconventional application, [Avro 504s](/Avro_504) sold to China, originally intended as trainers, were pressed into combat during the chaotic [warlord era](/Warlord_era). In a display of grim ingenuity, pilots would act as improvised bombers, dropping hand grenades and modified mortar shells directly from the cockpit onto enemy troops below. One can only imagine the precision of such an attack, or the sheer terror it must have inspired. (One might also note the need for a [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) for such a truly spectacular detail, but we’ll let it pass for now.)

The story of the 504 wasn't just about wartime improvisation and post-war repurposing. In 1925, [Avro](/Avro) introduced a significantly improved, redesigned variant: the radial-engined 504N, featuring an entirely new undercarriage. After evaluating two prototypes—one powered by the [Bristol Lucifer](/Bristol_Lucifer) and the other by the [Armstrong-Siddeley Lynx](/Armstrong-Siddeley_Lynx)—the Lynx-powered version was ultimately selected by the [RAF](/RAF) to replace the aging 504K as its primary trainer. A respectable 592 units of the 504N were manufactured between 1925 and 1932, equipping the RAF's five flying training schools and also serving as reliable communication aircraft. The 504N also found a significant export market, being sold to the armed forces of Belgium, Brazil, Chile, Denmark, Greece, Siam, and South Africa. Furthermore, licensed production of this improved variant took place in Denmark, Belgium, Canada, Siam, and Japan, extending its global footprint even further.

The [RAF](/RAF)'s 504Ns finally saw their official replacement in 1933 by the more modern [Avro Tutor](/Avro_Tutor). However, small numbers of the resilient 504N continued to serve in civilian capacities until 1940, when seven of them were re-impressed into [RAF](/RAF) service during [World War II](/World_War_II). Their final, somewhat ignominious, role was for target- and glider-towing, a far cry from their original, more combat-oriented aspirations, but a testament to their enduring airworthiness.

The [Avro 504](/Avro_504) holds a peculiar place in aviation history, credited with several "firsts" that belie its humble appearance. It was the first British aeroplane to engage in [strafing](/Strafing) troops on the ground, a grim innovation of aerial warfare. As previously mentioned, it was also the first British aircraft to conduct a bombing raid over Germany. Furthermore, it holds the unfortunate distinction of being the first Allied aeroplane to be shot down by enemy [anti-aircraft](/Anti-aircraft) fire. On a more positive note, it was the initial training platform for many future aces, including the legendary [Billy Bishop](/Billy_Bishop), giving countless pilots their first taste of flight.

One of its most visually distinctive features, easily recognizable even to the casual observer, is the single skid located prominently between its main landing gear wheels. This rather practical addition was affectionately, or perhaps derisively, referred to as the "toothpick" within the [RAF](/RAF). (One might again note the lack of a [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) for RAF slang, but it's a detail that adds character.)

## Variants

The [Avro 504](/Avro_504) family, despite its relatively simple and enduring core design, spawned a multitude of variants over its long production life. Each modification, however minor, aimed to adapt the aircraft for specific roles, accommodate different engines, or simply improve upon the original. It’s almost as if they couldn’t quite leave well enough alone.

*   **504:** The progenitor, the original sin, if you will. Powered by an 80&#160;hp (60&#160;kW) [Gnome Lambda](/Gnome_Lambda) engine. This was the blueprint for nearly two decades of persistent aviation.
*   **504A:** A subtly tweaked version of the original. This variant featured smaller ailerons and broader interplane struts, minor adjustments that likely made little difference to anyone but the most fastidious engineers. Still ran on the 80&#160;hp (60&#160;kW) Gnome engine.
*   **504B:** Developed for the [RNAS](/RNAS), this version incorporated a larger fin, presumably for improved stability in naval operations, or perhaps just because someone thought it looked better. It could be fitted with either the 80&#160;hp (60&#160;kW) Gnome or a [Le Rhône](/Le_Rh%C3%B4ne) engine.
*   **504C:** A rather specific, single-seat anti-[zeppelin](/Zeppelin) conversion for the [RNAS](/RNAS). The observer's cockpit was replaced with an extra fuel tank, extending its endurance for those long, cold patrols. A niche role, to be sure.
*   **504D:** The [Royal Flying Corps](/Royal_Flying_Corps)'s answer to the 504C, also a single-seat anti-zeppelin aircraft. Only six of these were ever built, suggesting it wasn't exactly a roaring success.
*   **504E:** Upgraded with a more powerful 100&#160;hp (75&#160;kW) [Gnome Monosoupape](/Gnome_Monosoupape) engine. A mere ten were produced, indicating it was likely an experimental stepping stone rather than a major production variant.
*   **504F:** A singular experiment, this variant was powered by a 75&#160;hp (56&#160;kW) [Rolls-Royce Hawk](/Rolls-Royce_Hawk) engine. One built. One can only assume it wasn't a resounding success.
*   **504G:** A two-seat weapons training variant specifically for the [RNAS](/RNAS), derived from the Type 504B. The [Avro 504G](/Avro_504) was envisioned as a platform for bombing and gunnery instruction, initially with provision for a Scarff ring mounting on the upper longerons. However, the final ten aircraft delivered mysteriously lacked any gun provisions. It retained the 80 hp Gnome powerplant. A total of 50 were built and delivered between June 1917 and January 1918, with 30 from Avro and 20 from The Regent Carriage Company.
*   **504H:** A 504C modified for [catapult](/Catapult) trials, powered by the 80&#160;hp (60&#160;kW) Gnome engine. Because launching aircraft from ships was clearly the next logical step in making pilots' lives more interesting.
*   **504J:** Essentially a 504A re-engined to accommodate the 100&#160;hp (75&#160;kW) Gnome engine. This variant proved more significant, leading into the mass-produced K-model. This particular [Avro 504K](/Avro_504) was, incidentally, the first aeroplane ever to grace the skies of Iceland, arriving in 1919.
*   **504K:** The undisputed king of the 504 family, this was the primary two-seat training aircraft. Its defining feature was a "universal mount" designed to accept a variety of engines, brilliantly solving the wartime problem of engine shortages. It could be fitted with a 130&#160;hp (97&#160;kW) [Clerget 9B](/Clerget_9B), a 100&#160;hp (75&#160;kW) [Gnome Monosoupape](/Gnome_Monosoupape), or a 110&#160;hp (82&#160;kW) [Le Rhône 9J](/Le_Rh%C3%B4ne_9J) engine. Many were also converted into single-seat fighters (dubbed "Comic" conversions) for anti-zeppelin duties. Several were even assembled in Australia by [Australian Aircraft & Engineering](/Australian_Aircraft_%26_Engineering). The [Qantas](/Qantas) 504K [Dyak](/Sunbeam_Dyak) from around 1921 is a notable example of its post-war civilian life.
*   **504K Mk.II:** A hybrid trainer, combining a 504K fuselage with the more modern 504N undercarriage and wings, while retaining a rotary engine. This variant was notably built under license in Mexico, where it was known as the Avro Anahuac.
*   **504L:** A floatplane version, proving that if it could fly, it could also float. It was powered by a 150&#160;hp (110&#160;kW) [Bentley](/Bentley) BR1, 130&#160;hp (97&#160;kW) Clerget, or 110&#160;hp (82&#160;kW) Le Rhône engines. The image of a 504L floatplane from 1920 is a quaint reminder of this amphibious adaptation.
*   **504M:** A curious three-seat cabin biplane. Only one was ever built, equipped with a 100&#160;hp (75&#160;kW) Gnome engine. A valiant attempt at passenger comfort, perhaps, but clearly not a commercial success.
*   **504N:** The post-war redesign, a significant leap forward for the 504. This two-seat training aircraft was specifically developed for the [RAF](/RAF) and featured a 160&#160;hp (120&#160;kW) [Armstrong Siddeley Lynx](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Lynx) engine. With 598 units built, it became the standard trainer for years. The distinct left-side view of the 504N highlights its refined appearance.
*   **504O:** The floatplane variant of the 504N. This particular model holds the distinction of being the first aircraft to fly above the [Arctic Circle](/Arctic_Circle) during the 1923 Oxford Expedition, proving that the 504, in its various guises, was truly global.
*   **504P:** An unbuilt project, envisioned as a 504N with side-by-side seating. Sometimes, ideas are best left on the drawing board.
*   **504Q:** Another three-seat cabin biplane, built specifically for the Oxford University Arctic Expedition. Only one was constructed, powered by an [Armstrong Siddeley Lynx](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Lynx) engine. A specialized vehicle for a very specialized expedition.
*   **504R Gosport:** A reworked trainer featuring a revised, lightweight structure. Five prototypes were flown between 1926 and 1927, experimenting with various engines including the 100&#160;hp (75&#160;kW) Gnome Monosoupape, 100&#160;hp (75&#160;kW) Avro Alpha, 140&#160;hp (104&#160;kW) [Armstrong Siddeley Genet Major](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Genet_Major), and the 150&#160;hp (110&#160;kW) [Armstrong Siddeley Mongoose](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Mongoose). The Mongoose was ultimately selected for the production models. Ten were sold to Argentina, with an additional 100 built under license by [FMA](/Lockheed_Martin_Aircraft_Argentina) in Argentina. Twelve were exported to Estonia, where they remained in service until 1940, and an unspecified number also went to Peru. The image of the 504R Gosport showcases its distinctive appearance.
*   **504S:** A two-seat training aircraft, produced under license in Japan by [Nakajima](/Nakajima_Aircraft_Company).
*   **540:** An observer training version of the 504K, specifically for the Japanese.
*   **582:** An experimental modification of the 504N. It featured new wings with an RAF 30 aerofoil section, [Frise ailerons](/Frise_aileron) on the bottom mainplanes, wing struts reduced to a more elegant "K" arrangement, and a simplified undercarriage. It was later converted back to 504N standard in 1928 to serve as a test bed for the Bristol Titan engine.
*   **585:** A 504R modified with the 504N undercarriage and a 90&#160;hp (67&#160;kW) Avro Alpha engine. Another minor experimental iteration in the long lineage.
*   **598 Warregull:** A two-seat trainer based on the 504N, intended for Australia, but ultimately not built.
*   **599 Warregull II:** A redesigned version of the Type 598, also remaining unbuilt.
*   **Yokosuka K2Y1:** The Japanese license-built version of the [Avro 504N](/Avro_504N), officially designated the Yokosuka Navy Type 3 Primary Trainer. Powered by a 130&#160;hp (97&#160;kW) [Mitsubishi](/Mitsubishi)-built [Armstrong Siddeley Mongoose](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Mongoose) radial piston engine, 104 units were produced. The image of the Yokosuka K2Y from 1938 illustrates its Japanese adaptation.
*   **Yokosuka K2Y2:** An improved iteration of the K2Y1, featuring a more powerful 160&#160;hp (120&#160;kW) Gasuden Jimpu 2 radial piston engine. A total of 360 K2Y1 and K2Y2 models were built. Watanabe-built aircraft of this type received the lengthy designation Watanabe Navy Type 3-2 Land-based Primary Trainer.
*   **U-1 (Uchebnyi – 1) Avrushka:** The Russian copy of the 504K, a testament to its universal appeal and ease of replication. Over 700 of these were built, effectively becoming the backbone of early Soviet flight training.
*   **MU-1 (Morskoy Uchebnyi – 1):** The Russian seaplane version of the U-1, proving that even copies can have their own variants.
*   **Orlogsværftet Flyvemaskineværksted LB.I:** The designation for Danish production of the 504 at the [Royal Naval Dockyard](/Orlogsv%C3%A6rftet) (Orlogsværftet), another example of widespread licensed manufacturing.
*   **I1A:** The [Brazilian Navy](/Brazilian_Navy) designation for their 504K models.
*   **I2A:** The Brazilian Navy designation for their 504N and 504O models.
*   **B.F.4 ([Thai](/Thai_language): บ.ฝ.๔):** The [Royal Siamese Air Force](/Royal_Thai_Air_Force) designation for their 504N aircraft.

## Operators

The [Avro 504](/Avro_504)'s operational reach was truly global, a testament to its simple efficacy and affordability. It became the default choice for numerous nascent air forces and established military aviation branches alike. One might say it was the aviation equivalent of a reliable, if somewhat unexciting, sedan – everyone needed one.

