## Surviving aircraft and replicas

Given its prolific production and enduring legacy, it’s hardly surprising that a number of [Avro 504s](/Avro_504), or at least faithful replicas, have managed to persist. They stand as tangible, if somewhat dusty, reminders of a bygone era, allowing future generations to marvel at the sheer audacity of early flight.

### Australia

*   **A3-4 – 504K:** This particular [504K](/Avro_504K) is on static display at the [Australian War Memorial](/Australian_War_Memorial) in [Campbell, Australian Capital Territory](/Campbell,_Australian_Capital_Territory). It began its life with the serial number H2174 before being dispatched to Australia around 1918–19. It was generously donated to the memorial in August 1929. In 1965, it was loaned to [Qantas](/Qantas) and underwent restoration to emulate the appearance of the very first Qantas aircraft. However, it was later returned to its original condition and sent back to the Australian War Memorial in 1987, presumably after someone realized historical accuracy was more important than corporate branding.
*   **Replica – 504K:** A replica of the [504K](/Avro_504K) is on static display at the [Qantas Founders Outback Museum](/Qantas_Founders_Outback_Museum) in [Longreach, Queensland](/Longreach,_Queensland). Constructed in 1988, it bears the markings G-AUBG, representing the first [Qantas](/Qantas) Avro 504K. (One might wonder if they simply ran out of original aircraft to restore.)
*   **Replica – 504K:** Another replica of the [504K](/Avro_504K) can be found on static display at [Sydney Airport](/Sydney_Airport) in Sydney. Also built in 1988 and marked as G-AUBG, it too represents the inaugural [Qantas](/Qantas) Avro 504K. (One might observe a pattern here: if you can't find the real thing, build a good copy and put it everywhere.)
*   **Replica – 504K:** This replica [504K](/Avro_504K) is on static display at the [RAAF Museum](/RAAF_Museum) in [Point Cook, Victoria](/Point_Cook,_Victoria). What makes this one slightly more interesting is that it incorporates an original engine, various fittings, and period instruments. It is marked as E3747, a nod to its historical roots despite being a modern construction.

### Canada

*   **H2453 – 504K:** This [504K](/Avro_504K) is proudly on static display at the [Canada Aviation and Space Museum](/Canada_Aviation_and_Space_Museum) in [Ottawa](/Ottawa), Ontario. It previously held the civilian registration G-CYFG and was once part of [Cole Palen](/Cole_Palen)'s collection, a man known for his dedication to vintage aircraft.
*   **Replica – 504K:** A replica [504K](/Avro_504K) is on static display at the [Base Borden Military Museum](/Base_Borden_Military_Museum) at [CFB Borden](/CFB_Borden) near [Angus, Ontario](/Angus,_Ontario). This particular replica is on loan from the [Canada Aviation and Space Museum](/Canada_Aviation_and_Space_Museum) and previously had the registration G-CYCK, having been owned by J.S. Appleby before its museum tenure.

### Finland

*   **AV-57 – 504K:** This [504K](/Avro_504K) is currently held in storage at the [Finnish Airforce Museum](/Finnish_Airforce_Museum) in [Tikkakoski, Jyväskylä](/Tikkakoski). A rare survivor, patiently awaiting its moment in the spotlight, or perhaps just a good clean.

### New Zealand

*   **A202 – 504K:** Remarkably, this [504K](/Avro_504K) is airworthy and can be found at The Vintage Aviator in [Masterton, Wellington](/Masterton). It was originally purchased by the New Zealand Permanent Air Force in 1925, before embarking on a civilian career. Its continued airworthiness is a testament to meticulous restoration and the enduring appeal of these early designs.

### Norway

*   **Unknown – 504K:** A [504K](/Avro_504K) is on static display at the [Norwegian Aviation Museum](/Norwegian_Aviation_Museum) in [Bodø, Nordland](/Bod%C3%B8). It saw active service from July 1921 until 1928 and has been a museum exhibit since 1995. It bears the registration number 103, which, rather ironically, belonged to a 504A that crashed in 1919. A subtle nod to its less fortunate brethren, perhaps.

### Russia

*   **Replica – 504K:** An airworthy replica [504K](/Avro_504K) is located in Russia. It was previously exhibited at the [Military Aviation Museum](/Military_Aviation_Museum) in [Virginia Beach, Virginia](/Virginia_Beach,_Virginia). It has been assigned the serial number "H5991" and is painted in the colors of the [Royal Flying Corps](/Royal_Flying_Corps), a rather fitting tribute to its origins.

### United Kingdom

*   **BK892 – 504K:** This airworthy [504K](/Avro_504K) is a prize possession of the [Shuttleworth Collection](/Shuttleworth_Collection) in [Old Warden, Bedfordshire](/Old_Warden). Originally bearing the serial number H5199, it was later converted to a 504N and sold into civilian ownership. However, destiny had other plans, and it was re-impressed into [RAF](/RAF) service during [World War II](/World_War_II) as a glider tug, acquiring a new serial number in the process. After the war, it returned to civilian use and even featured in the filming of *Reach for the Sky*, proving its cinematic versatility.
*   **D7560 – 504K:** A [504K](/Avro_504K) is on static display at the [Science Museum](/Science_Museum,_London) in London. A perfect place for a machine that represents a pivotal moment in technological history.
*   **H2311 – 504K:** This [504K](/Avro_504K) can be found on static display at the [Museum of Science and Industry](/Museum_of_Science_and_Industry_(Manchester)) in Manchester, a fitting home given [Avro](/Avro)'s roots.
*   **Composite – 504K:** A rather unique [504K](/Avro_504K) is on static display at the [Royal Air Force Museum London](/Royal_Air_Force_Museum_London) in London. This particular exhibit is a composite, ingeniously constructed from the fuselage of G-EBJE and the wings of G-EBKN, a testament to resourcefulness and the enduring presence of spare parts.
*   **Replica – 504K:** A replica [504K](/Avro_504K) is on static display at the [Brooklands Museum](/Brooklands_Museum) in [Weybridge, Surrey](/Weybridge,_Surrey). Marked as G-AACA, this machine was initially built as a taxiable replica for the 1970s BBC TV series 'Wings'. It was later acquired by the [RAF Museum](/Royal_Air_Force_Museum_London), Hendon, stored at RAF Henlow, and eventually loaned to Brooklands Museum around 1987. It was subsequently donated to the museum, fitted with an original rotary engine, and restored to represent one of two 504s operated by the Brooklands School of Flying in the late 1920s and early 1930s.
*   **Replica – 504J:** A replica [504J](/Avro_504J) is on static display at [Solent Sky](/Solent_Sky) in [Southampton, Hampshire](/Southampton,_Hampshire). It is marked as C4451 and was constructed by ADJ, bearing the BAPC No 210 designation.
*   **Replica – 504K:** This replica [504K](/Avro_504K) was built by Pursang in Argentina in 2010. It was then acquired by Eric Vernon-Roe, the grandson of Alliot Vernon-Roe, the founder of [Avro](/Avro), and subsequently brought to the UK. Registered as G-EROE, it now regularly performs with the Great War Display Team, keeping the spirit of the Avro 504 alive in the skies.

### United States

*   **A201 – 504:** A genuine [Avro 504](/Avro_504) is currently undergoing restoration at Blue Swallow Aircraft in [Earlysville, Virginia](/Earlysville,_Virginia). A slow, meticulous process, no doubt.
*   **Replica – 504:** Another replica [504](/Avro_504) is under construction at Blue Swallow Aircraft in Earlysville, Virginia, ensuring that the legacy continues.
*   **Replica – 504K:** A replica [504K](/Avro_504K) is undergoing work to become airworthy at the [Old Rhinebeck Aerodrome](/Old_Rhinebeck_Aerodrome) in [Red Hook, New York](/Red_Hook,_New_York). This particular machine has been flying, in one form or another, since 1971, a testament to its enduring design and the dedication of its caretakers.
*   **Replica – 504K:** This replica [504K](/Avro_504K) is on static display at the [National Museum of the United States Air Force](/National_Museum_of_the_United_States_Air_Force) in [Dayton, Ohio](/Dayton,_Ohio). It was meticulously constructed between 1966 and 1967 by the [Royal Canadian Air Force](/Royal_Canadian_Air_Force)'s Aircraft Maintenance & Development Unit and arrived at the museum in May 2003. It previously held the registration G-CYEI, another artifact of its Canadian origins.

## Specifications (Avro 504K)

For those who simply must delve into the numbers, here are the dry, unromantic facts for the [Avro 504K](/Avro_504K). Data derived from "The Encyclopedia of World Aircraft" and "Jane's Fighting Aircraft of World War I" – sources that, one assumes, were not known for their effusive prose. The dimensioned drawing of the Russian U-1 Avrushka, reverse-engineered by [Sergey Ilyushin](/Sergey_Ilyushin) around 1923, offers a parallel view into the enduring design.

### General characteristics

*   **Crew:** 2 (Pilot and a rather exposed observer/student, whose primary job was probably to look terrified or try not to fall out).
*   **Length:** 29&#160;ft 5&#160;in (8.97&#160;m). Not exactly a behemoth, but respectable for its era.
*   **Wingspan:** 36&#160;ft 0&#160;in (10.97&#160;m). A generous spread for stability and lift.
*   **Height:** 10&#160;ft 5&#160;in (3.18&#160;m). Tall enough to make pre-flight checks a minor athletic endeavor.
*   **Wing area:** 330&#160;sq&#160;ft (31&#160;m 2 ). Plenty of surface area to catch the air, and occasionally the ground.
*   **Empty weight:** 1,231&#160;lb (558&#160;kg). Light enough to be agile, heavy enough to feel substantial.
*   **Gross weight:** 1,829&#160;lb (830&#160;kg). Fully loaded, it certainly felt its weight.
*   **Fuel capacity:** 25.5&#160;imp&#160;gal (31&#160;US&#160;gal; 116&#160;L) of fuel, plus 6&#160;imp&#160;gal (7&#160;US&#160;gal; 27&#160;L) of [castor oil](/Castor_oil). The castor oil was for the rotary engine, ensuring that every flight was a well-lubricated, if somewhat aromatic, experience for the pilot.
*   **Powerplant:** 1 × [Le Rhône 9J](/Le_Rh%C3%B4ne_9J) 9-cylinder air-cooled rotary piston engine, delivering a modest 110&#160;hp (82&#160;kW). This was one of the common engine choices for the K-model, a reliable if somewhat peculiar power source.
*   **Propellers:** 2-bladed [Avro](/Avro) fixed-pitch wooden propeller, with a diameter of 9&#160;ft 0&#160;in (2.74&#160;m) and a pitch of 8&#160;ft 8&#160;in (2.6&#160;m). Simple, effective, and prone to splintering upon impact.

### Performance

*   **Maximum speed:**
    *   95&#160;mph (153&#160;km/h, 83&#160;kn) at sea level. A respectable clip for 1913, less so for 1918.
    *   87&#160;mph (76&#160;kn; 140&#160;km/h) at 8,000&#160;ft (2,400&#160;m). Altitude, as always, takes its toll.
    *   85&#160;mph (74&#160;kn; 137&#160;km/h) at 10,000&#160;ft (3,000&#160;m). Not exactly blistering.
*   **Cruise speed:**
    *   74&#160;mph (119&#160;km/h, 64&#160;kn) at 75% power at 8,000&#160;ft (2,400&#160;m). For those leisurely patrols or training flights.
    *   71&#160;mph (62&#160;kn; 114&#160;km/h) at 75% power at 10,000&#160;ft (3,000&#160;m). Even more leisurely.
*   **Stall speed:** 40&#160;mph (64&#160;km/h, 35&#160;kn). A fairly forgiving stall speed, which was probably appreciated by new students.
*   **Range:** 250&#160;mi (400&#160;km, 220&#160;nmi). Enough to get around, but not across continents.
*   **Endurance:**
    *   2 hours at sea level at maximum speed. Hope you didn't forget anything.
    *   2 hours 8 minutes at 8,000&#160;ft (2,400&#160;m) at maximum speed. A whole 8 extra minutes!
    *   3 hours at 10,000&#160;ft (3,000&#160;m) at maximum speed. The higher you go, the longer you can stay, apparently.
    *   3 hours 42 minutes at 8,000&#160;ft (2,400&#160;m) at cruise speed. Now we're talking.
    *   4 hours 15 minutes at 10,000&#160;ft (3,000&#160;m) at cruise speed. Plenty of time to get bored or lost.
*   **Service ceiling:** 16,000&#160;ft (4,900&#160;m). High enough to avoid some ground fire, not high enough to avoid all problems.
*   **Rate of climb:** 700&#160;ft/min (3.6&#160;m/s). Not exactly a rocket, but it got there eventually.
*   **Time to altitude:**
    *   3,500&#160;ft (1,100&#160;m) in 5 minutes.
    *   8,000&#160;ft (2,400&#160;m) in 10 minutes.
    *   10,000&#160;ft (3,000&#160;m) in 16 minutes. A leisurely ascent, perfect for contemplation.
*   **Wing loading:** 5.54&#160;lb/sq&#160;ft (27.0&#160;kg/m 2 ). Lightly loaded, contributing to its forgiving flight characteristics.
*   **[Power/mass](/Power-to-weight_ratio):** 0.06&#160;hp/lb (0.099&#160;kW/kg). Not going to win any races, but it got the job done.

### Armament

*   1 fixed .303 [Lewis gun](/Lewis_gun) atop upper wing (single-seat night fighter variants). A rather last-ditch attempt at making a trainer into something more aggressive.

